<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-TbxI_oRSKI&feature=kp">Only Lovers Left Alive</a> was fantastic (Tilda Swinton is brilliant), a must-see for any music enthusiast, featuring some serious guitar porn and a great soundtrack. Hamdan, as well as her previous work with Soapkills, is a must-listen as well.</p>
<p>You can check some of Hamdan’s music out on her soundcloud <a href="https://soundcloud.com/yasminehamdan/">here</a>, and on my favorite place to see/listen to musicians, her first <a href="http://www.npr.org/event/music/314564700/yasmine-hamdan-tiny-desk-concert?ft=1&f=1039">Tiny Desk Concert</a>. Beautiful!</p><br><a rel="nofollow" href="http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/gocomments/melissatabeek2012.wordpress.com/2560/"><img alt="" border="0" src="http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/comments/melissatabeek2012.wordpress.com/2560/"></a> <img alt="" border="0" src="http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=melissatabeek.com&blog=35097313&post=2560&subd=melissatabeek2012&ref=&feed=1" width="1" height="1">";s:17:"post_image_height";i:667;s:16:"post_image_width";i:1000;s:11:"post_visits";i:15;s:18:"post_twitterShares";i:1;s:19:"post_facebookShares";i:8;s:16:"post_totalShares";i:9;s:16:"post_socialScore";i:24;s:13:"post_virality";i:18;s:9:"blog_name";s:14:"Melissa Tabeek";s:16:"blog_description";s:131:"Melissa Tabeek is a freelance journalist currently in Beirut, Lebanon, and reports on politics, culture and refugee-related issues.";s:8:"blog_url";s:25:"http://melissatabeek.com/";s:11:"blog_author";s:14:"Melissa Tabeek";s:28:"blog_author_twitter_username";s:13:"tabeekmelissa";s:13:"blog_rss_feed";s:30:"http://melissatabeek.com/feed/";s:9:"blog_tags";s:17:"society, politics";s:2:"id";i:291;s:11:"blog_active";i:1;s:24:"blog_last_post_timestamp";i:1401716160;}i:18;O:8:"stdClass":26:{s:7:"post_id";i:30288;s:8:"post_url";s:78:"http://www.beirutreport.com/2014/05/this-is-not-ariel-sharons-supermarket.html";s:10:"post_title";s:40:""This is not Ariel Sharon's supermarket"";s:10:"post_image";s:115:"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-oXDVbXYR-bU/U4TbReTVlcI/AAAAAAAAI94/hXDf-aBwFk4/s640/blogger-image-185132083.jpg";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:123:"So reads the banner above, placed just outside an old supermarket on Makdessi street in Hamra.A handful of police office...";s:7:"blog_id";s:12:"beirutreport";s:14:"post_timestamp";i:1401217380;s:12:"post_content";s:3067:"<div dir="ltr" trbidi="on"><br><div><a href="https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-oXDVbXYR-bU/U4TbReTVlcI/AAAAAAAAI94/hXDf-aBwFk4/s640/blogger-image-185132083.jpg" imageanchor="1"><img border="0" src="https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-oXDVbXYR-bU/U4TbReTVlcI/AAAAAAAAI94/hXDf-aBwFk4/s640/blogger-image-185132083.jpg"></a></div><br>So reads the banner above, placed just outside an old supermarket on Makdessi street in Hamra.<br><br><div><a href="https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/-vv4mrJ5CTdw/U4Ta5PAUYdI/AAAAAAAAI9o/Yph3PH4pfK8/s640/blogger-image--1756775565.jpg" imageanchor="1"><img border="0" height="640" src="https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/-vv4mrJ5CTdw/U4Ta5PAUYdI/AAAAAAAAI9o/Yph3PH4pfK8/s640/blogger-image--1756775565.jpg" width="480"></a></div><br>A handful of police officers stood across the street. Neighbors watching told me the tenant was being evicted after having been offered somewhere around $100,000 to vacate both the shop and an apartment in the building, which is either being renovated or torn down. <br><br>I passed by later this evening and a number of people were still inside.<br><div><br></div><div><a href="https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-GTyO-FFUWIo/U4TayuK8CaI/AAAAAAAAI9g/36QtD2xfHzE/s640/blogger-image-2043986232.jpg" imageanchor="1"><img border="0" src="https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-GTyO-FFUWIo/U4TayuK8CaI/AAAAAAAAI9g/36QtD2xfHzE/s640/blogger-image-2043986232.jpg"></a></div><br>One woman, who described herself as a relative of the shopkeeper, said she planned to sleep in between the aisles tonight along with other relatives. She said the shopkeeper--an older woman-- had been running the Aintoury Market since 1960s. The fear is that repossession team will gut the place at night after having already dragged the refrigerators out on the street.<br><br><div><a href="https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/-x3nOFCPhCSk/U4TacTYCWRI/AAAAAAAAI9Q/KROw5QKBV9A/s640/blogger-image--1185394548.jpg" imageanchor="1"><img border="0" src="https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/-x3nOFCPhCSk/U4TacTYCWRI/AAAAAAAAI9Q/KROw5QKBV9A/s640/blogger-image--1185394548.jpg"></a></div><div><br></div><div>But this woman told me only $60,000 had been offered both to vacate the shop and the shopkeeper's 130 square apartment. Obviously both properties in a prime Hamra location would be valued in the millions of dollars but the woman is an old renter, though she says she was promised much more by the court. ($60,000 is barely enough to rent a parking space in today's real estate market.)</div><div><br></div><div>"Do you think they are kicking us out because we are Christian," she asked me in a hushed tone. I told her people are being evicted from the city no matter what their religion. She nodded and then gave an example of another Muslim woman being kicked out of her building down the block. </div><div><br></div><div>I asked why they had listed infamous Israeli general "Ariel Sharon" on the banner. "Ariel Sharon is the enemy isn't he," she said. "Are we the enemy too?"</div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div></div>";s:17:"post_image_height";i:480;s:16:"post_image_width";i:640;s:11:"post_visits";i:23;s:18:"post_twitterShares";i:13;s:19:"post_facebookShares";i:143;s:16:"post_totalShares";i:156;s:16:"post_socialScore";i:43;s:13:"post_virality";i:40;s:9:"blog_name";s:17:"The Beirut Report";s:16:"blog_description";s:56:"An inside look at Lebanon, the Middle East and its media";s:8:"blog_url";s:23:"http://beirutreport.com";s:11:"blog_author";s:12:"Habib Battah";s:28:"blog_author_twitter_username";s:7:"habib_b";s:13:"blog_rss_feed";s:47:"http://www.beirutreport.com/feeds/posts/default";s:9:"blog_tags";s:17:"society, politics";s:2:"id";i:17;s:11:"blog_active";i:1;s:24:"blog_last_post_timestamp";i:1401566160;}i:19;O:8:"stdClass":26:{s:7:"post_id";i:30284;s:8:"post_url";s:80:"http://dreamofchange.wordpress.com/2014/05/27/samir-geagea-discovers-calculator/";s:10:"post_title";s:37:"Samir Geagea discovers calculator….";s:10:"post_image";s:0:"";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:123:"A media and news frenzy has been sweeping through the country ever since Dr. Samir Geagea (Also known as the white Nels...";s:7:"blog_id";s:13:"dreamofchange";s:14:"post_timestamp";i:1401211020;s:12:"post_content";s:3326:"<p><a href="http://dreamofchange.files.wordpress.com/2014/05/calculator.jpg"><img src="http://dreamofchange.files.wordpress.com/2014/05/calculator.jpg?w=700" alt="calculator"></a></p>
<p>A media and news frenzy has been sweeping through the country ever since Dr. Samir Geagea (Also known as the white Nelson Mandella….) expressed his willingness to withdraw his candidacy for president of the Lebanese “republic”.</p>
<p>There have been many analysis as to what might have sparked this move and what it’s political origins were.</p>
<p>The T times was able to get inside information from a source that will remain anonymous, embedded deep inside the walls of the Maarab palace.<br>
The source has revealed that there was a very very big dispute in the household of Dr. Geagea before the decision was made public. Apparently MP Strida Geagea has missed out on a crucial piece of information to pass on to husband Samir concerning the advancements in technology during his 14 years in jail.</p>
<p>According to the source; while Dr. Samir did learned how to Google stuff, watch youtube videos, play candy crush and tweet; Setrida has failed to tell him that calculators were now no longer the size of a room.<br>
Upon discovery of the device, Samir immediately realized the power of what he now held between his palms. A device that would allow him to calculate the number of MP’s needed for him to become president.</p>
<p>Samir immediately Googled “How to use calculator”. and followed the instructions.</p>
<p>128 – 48 = 80</p>
<p>128 – 48= 80</p>
<p>…</p>
<p>128 – 48= 80</p>
<p>…</p>
<p><strong><em>“Damn it…. How many people know of this device Setrida?”</em> asked Samir</strong></p>
<p>Setrida: <em>“<strong>Well…. Everyone”</strong></em><strong> .</strong></p>
<p>Samir: <strong><em>“Are you saying EVERYONE knew that I would not win?” </em></strong></p>
<p>Setrida: <strong><em>“I thought it was some sort of political game you were playing!” </em></strong></p>
<p>Samir:<strong><em> “what do you mean political gamess! Do you know how much money I spent on billboards and slogans trying to pressure them to open the parliament for a voting session!”  </em></strong></p>
<p>Setrida: <em><strong>“You can now use the calculator to calculate that amount honey! See there is a bright side to everything!”</strong></em></p>
<p>When asked about Samir’s recent discovery of the calculator, Michel Aoun replied <strong><em>“Baarrrghhh…. Wisshh ghaa… mmmm… Agghhh..rrr</em></strong>” and then stormed out of the room.</p>
<p>In an emergency meeting, the office of the prime minister made a decision to provide weekly courses, to old peeps like Nabih, Walid, Samir, Michel and others, in order to make sure that they are always up to date with recent discoveries. Courses will include discoveries such as ipads, iphones, selfies and the constitution.</p>
<p> </p>
